==B==

{{glossary}}
{{term|term= '''[[B cell]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A type of lymphocyte in the humoral immunity of the adaptive immune system.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bacteria]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An enormous and diverse clade of microscopic, [[prokaryote|prokaryotic]], single-[[Cell (biology)|cell]]ed organisms which lack a true [[Cell nucleus|nucleus]]. They represent one of the three biological [[domain (biology)|domain]]s.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bacteriophage]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A [[virus]] that infects and multiplies within bacteria.}}

{{term|term= '''[[Barr body]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The inactive X chromosome in a female somatic cell, rendered inactive in a process called lyonization, in those species in which sex is determined by the presence of the Y (including humans) or W chromosome rather than the diploidy of the X or Z.}}

{{term|term= '''[[basal body]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An organelle formed from a [[centriole]], and a short cylindrical array of microtubules. Also called a ''basal granule'', a ''kinetosome'', and in older cytological literature, a ''blepharoplast''.}}

{{term|term= '''[[behavioral ecology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the evolutionary basis for animal behavior due to ecological pressures.}}

{{term|term= '''[[benthic zone]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The ecological region at the lowest level of a body of water such as an ocean or a lake, including the sediment surface and some sub-surface layers.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bile]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A dark green to yellowish-brown fluid, produced by the liver of most vertebrates, which aids the digestion of [[lipid]]s in the small intestine. Also called ''gall''.}}

{{term|term= '''[[Fission (biology)|binary fission]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The process by which one prokaryotic cell divides into two identical daughter cells.}}

{{term|term= '''[[binomial nomenclature]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A formal system of classifying [[species]] of living things by giving each a name composed of two parts, both of which use Latin grammatical forms, although they can be based on words from other languages.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biocatalysis]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The process of [[catalysis]] in biological systems. In biocatalytic processes, natural catalysts, such as protein enzymes, perform chemical transformations on organic compounds.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biochemistry]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The branch of biology that explores the chemical processes within and related to living organisms.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biodiversity]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A contraction of "biological diversity" generally referring to the variety and variability of life on Earth.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bioengineering]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of concepts and methods of biology to solve real-world problems related to the life sciences or the application thereof.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bioenergetics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the transformation of energy in living organisms.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biogeography]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the distribution of species and ecosystems in geographic space and through geological time. Organisms and biological communities often vary in a regular fashion along geographic gradients of latitude, elevation, isolation and habitat area.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bioinformatics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of computer technology to the management of biological information.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biological organization]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= the hierarchy of complex biological structures and systems, designed to define life through a reductionist approach.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of life and organisms.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomass]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= Organic matter derived from living or recently living organisms. Biomass can be used as a source of energy and it most often refers to plants or plant-based materials which are not used for food or feed, and are specifically called lignocellulosic biomass.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomathematics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The theoretical use of mathematical models and abstractions of living systems to understand and predict biological problems.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biome]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A very large ecological area on the Earth's surface containing fauna and flora (animals and plants) adapting to their environment. Biomes are often defined by abiotic factors such as climate, topographical relief, geology, soils, and water resources.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomechanics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the structure and function of biological systems by means of the methods of "mechanics", which is the branch of physics involving analysis of the actions of forces.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomedical engineering]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of engineering principles and design concepts to medicine and biology for healthcare purposes (e.g. diagnostic or therapeutic).}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomedical research]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The pursuit of answers to medical questions. These investigations lead to discoveries, which in turn lead to the development of new preventions, therapies, and cures for problems in human and veterinary health. Biomedical research generally takes two forms: basic science and applied research.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomimetic]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The imitation of the models, systems, and elements of [[nature]] for the purpose of solving complex human problems.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biomolecule]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A loosely used term for [[molecules]] and [[ions]] that are present in organisms, essential to some typically biological process such as [[cell division]], [[morphogenesis]], or development.}}

{{term|term= '''[[bionics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of biological methods and systems found in nature to the study and design of engineering systems and modern technology. Also known as ''biomimetics'', ''biognosis'', ''biomimicry'', or ''bionical creativity engineering''.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biophysics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of approaches traditionally employed in physics to study biological systems.}}

{{term|term= '''[[biotechnology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= Biotechnology is the use of living systems and organisms to develop or make products, or "any technological application that uses biological systems, living organisms or derivatives thereof, to make or modify products or processes for specific use" (UN Convention on Biological Diversity).}}

{{term|term= '''[[bipedal]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A form of terrestrial locomotion where an organism moves by means of its two rear limbs or legs.}}

{{term|term= '''[[blastocyst]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A mammalian [[blastula]] in which some differentiation of cells has occurred.}}

{{term|term= '''[[blood]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The red liquid that circulates in the arteries and veins of humans and other vertebrate animals, carrying oxygen to and carbon dioxide from the tissues of the body.}}

{{term|term= '''[[blood-brain barrier]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A semipermeable membrane separating the blood from the cerebrospinal fluid, and constituting a barrier to the passage of cells, particles, and large molecules.}}

{{term|term= '''[[botany]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of plants.}}

{{term|term= '''[[Bowman's capsule]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A cup-like sac at the beginning of the tubular component of a [[nephron]] in the mammalian kidney that performs the first step in the filtration of blood to form urine. A [[glomerulus]] is enclosed in the sac. Also known as ''capsula glomeruli'' or ''glomerular capsule''.}}

{{term|term= '''[[building biology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A science that leads to natural healthy ecological homes, schools, and workplaces that exist in harmony with the environment.}}

