==P==

{{glossary}}
{{term|term= '''[[paleontology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the history of life on Earth as reflected in the fossil record. Fossils are the remains or traces of organisms (plants, animals, fungi, bacteria and other single-celled living things) that lived in the geological past and are preserved in the crust of the Earth.}}

{{term|term= '''[[parallel evolution]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The development of a similar trait in related, but distinct, species descending from the same [[ancestor]], but from different clades.}}

{{term|term= '''[[parasitology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of parasites, their hosts, and the relationship between them. As a biological discipline, the scope of parasitology is not determined by the organism or environment in question, but by their way of life.}}

{{term|term= '''[[pathobiology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study or practice of pathology with greater emphasis on the biological than on the medical aspects.}}

{{term|term= '''[[pathology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A medical specialty that is concerned with the diagnosis of disease based on the laboratory analysis of bodily fluids such as blood and urine, as well as tissues, using the tools of chemistry, clinical microbiology, hematology and molecular pathology.}}

{{term|term= '''[[pH]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A numeric scale used to specify the acidity or basicity (alkalinity) of an aqueous solution. It is roughly the negative of the logarithm to base 10 of the concentration, measured in units of moles per liter, of hydrogen ions.}}

{{term|term= '''[[pharmacology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The science of drug action on biological systems. In its entirety, it embraces knowledge of the sources, chemical properties, biological effects and therapeutic uses of drugs.}}

{{term|term= '''[[phenotype]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The composite of an organism's observable features or traits, such as its morphology, development, biochemical or physiological properties, behavior, and products of behavior.}}

{{term|term= '''[[pheromone]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A secreted or excreted chemical factor that triggers a social response in members of the same [[species]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[phloem]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The conducting tissue in plants responsible for the conduction of food particles.}}

{{term|term= '''[[physiology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= the branch of biology dealing with the functions and activities of living organisms and their parts, including all physical and chemical processes.}}

{{term|term= '''[[phytochemistry]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of [[phytochemicals]], which are chemicals derived from plants.}}

{{term|term= '''[[phytopathology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The science of diagnosing and managing plant diseases.}}

{{term|term= '''[[placebo]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A [[Chemical substance|substance]] or treatment of no intended therapeutic value.}}

{{term|term= '''[[plant nutrition]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of the chemical elements and compounds necessary for plant growth, plant [[metabolism]] and their external supply.}}

{{term|term= '''[[plasmolysis]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The process in which [[Cell (biology)|cells]] lose water in a [[hypertonic solution]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[pollination]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The transfer of [[pollen]] from a male part of a plant to a female part of a plant, enabling later fertilisation and the production of seeds, most often by an animal or by wind.}}

{{term|term= '''[[polygene]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A member of a group of non-epistatic genes that interact additively to influence a [[phenotypic]] trait.}}

{{term|term= '''[[polymer]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A large molecule, or  [[macromolecule]], composed of many repeated subunits.}}

{{term|term= '''[[polymerase chain reaction]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A technique used in [[molecular biology]] to amplify a single copy or a few copies of a segment of [[DNA]] across several orders of magnitude, generating thousands to millions of copies of a particular [[DNA]] sequence.}}

{{term|term= '''[[polyploid]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The cells and organisms are those containing more than two paired sets of [[chromosomes]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[population biology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of populations of organisms, especially the regulation of population size, life history traits such as clutch size, and extinction.}}

{{term|term= '''[[population ecology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A subfield of ecology that deals with the dynamics of species populations and how these populations interact with the environment. It is the study of how the population sizes of species change over time and space. Also called ''autoecology''.}}

{{term|term= '''[[population genetics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The study of genetic variation within populations, involving the examination and modelling of changes in the frequencies of genes and alleles in populations across space and time.}}

{{term|term= '''[[predation]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A biological interaction where a [[predator]] kills and eats its [[prey]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[primase]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An [[enzyme]] involved in the replication of [[DNA]] and is a type of [[RNA polymerase]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[Primer (molecular biology)|primer]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A short strand of [[RNA]] or [[DNA]] that serves as a starting point for [[DNA synthesis]].}}

{{term|term= '''[[progesterone]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An endogenous steroid and progestogen sex [[hormone]] which is part of the [[menstrual cycle]], [[pregnancy]], and [[embryogenesis]] of humans and other species.}}

{{term|term= '''[[prokaryote]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= An organism which does not have a true nucleus.}}

{{term|term= '''[[protein]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A polypeptide chain of amino acids. It is a body-building nutrient.}}

{{term|term= '''[[protein structure]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= A three-dimensional arrangement of [[atoms]] in an amino acid-chain molecule.}}

{{term|term= '''[[Proxemics]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= is the study of human use of space and the effects that population density has on behaviour, communication, and social interaction.}}

{{term|term= '''[[psychobiology]]'''}}
{{defn|defn= The application of the principles of biology to the study of physiological, genetic, and developmental mechanisms of behavior in humans and other animals. Also called ''behavioral neuroscience'', ''biological psychology'', and ''biopsychology''.}}

{{glossary end}}

