{{redirect|HARPS|other uses|Harp (disambiguation)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}
[[Image:HARPS Spectrograph and the 3.6m Telescope.jpg|thumb|245px|Montage of the HARPS spectrograph and the 3.6m telescope at La Silla. The upper left shows the dome of the telescope, while the upper right illustrates the telescope itself. The HARPS spectrograph is shown in the lower image during laboratory tests. The vacuum tank is open so that some of the high-precision components inside can be seen]]
The '''High Accuracy Radial velocity Planet Searcher''' ('''HARPS''') is a high-precision [[Echelle grating|echelle]] planet finding [[spectrograph]] installed in 2002 on the [[ESO 3.6 m Telescope|ESO's 3.6m telescope]] at [[La Silla Observatory]] in [[Chile]]. The [[First light (astronomy)|first light]] was achieved in February 2003. HARPS has discovered over 130 [[exoplanet]]s to date, with the first one in 2004, making it the most successful planet finder behind the [[Kepler space observatory]]. It is a second-generation [[radial velocity method|radial-velocity]] spectrograph, based on experience with the [[ELODIE spectrograph|ELODIE]] and [[CORALIE spectrograph|CORALIE]] instruments.<ref name="HARPS">{{cite journal | title=Setting New Standards With HARPS | url=http://www.eso.org/sci/facilities/lasilla/instruments/harps/science/papers/harps_mess114.pdf | author=Mayor ''et al.'' | journal=ESO Messenger | volume=114 | pages=20 | date=2003 | bibcode=2003Msngr.114...20M | last2=Pepe | first2=F. | last3=Queloz | first3=D. | last4=Bouchy | first4=F. | last5=Rupprecht | first5=G. | last6=Lo Curto | first6=G. | last7=Avila | first7=G. | last8=Benz | first8=W. | last9=Bertaux | first9=J.-L. | last10=Bonfils | first10=X. | last11=Dall | first11=Th. | last12=Dekker | first12=H. | last13=Delabre | first13=B. | last14=Eckert | first14=W. | last15=Fleury | first15=M. | last16=Gilliotte | first16=A. | last17=Gojak | first17=D. | last18=Guzman | first18=J. C. | last19=Kohler | first19=D. | last20=Lizon | first20=J.-L. | last21=Longinotti | first21=A. | last22=Lovis | first22=C. | last23=Megevand | first23=D. | last24=Pasquini | first24=L. | last25=Reyes | first25=J. | last26=Sivan | first26=J.-P. | last27=Sosnowska | first27=D. | last28=Soto | first28=R. | last29=Udry | first29=S. | last30=Van Kesteren | first30=A. | display-authors=9 }}</ref>
==Characteristics== HARPS can attain a precision of 0.97&nbsp;m/s (3.5&nbsp;km/h),<ref name="cnn.com">{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/TECH/science/10/19/space.new.planets/index.html | work=CNN | title=32 planets discovered outside solar system - CNN.com | accessdate=4 May 2010 | date=19 October 2009}}</ref> with an effective precision of the order of 30&nbsp;cm s<sup>−1</sup>,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espresso.astro.up.pt/ |title=ESPRESSO – Searching for other Worlds |date=16 December 2009 |publisher=Centro de Astrofísica da Universidade do Porto |accessdate=2010-10-16}}</ref>{{Off-topic-inline}} making it one of only two instruments worldwide with such accuracy.<ref name="auto">citation needed</ref> This is due to a design in which the target star and a reference spectrum from a [[thorium]] lamp are observed simultaneously using two identical [[optic fibre]] feeds, and to careful attention to mechanical stability: the instrument sits in a vacuum vessel which is temperature-controlled to within 0.01 kelvins.<ref>{{cite paper| url=http://www.eso.org/sci/facilities/lasilla/instruments/harps/science/papers/6269-25.pdf | work=ESO | title=The exoplanet hunter HARPS: unequalled accuracy and perspectives toward 1 cm.s-1 precision | accessdate=14 September 2011}}</ref> The precision and sensitivity of the instrument is such that it incidentally produced the best available measurement of the thorium spectrum.<ref name="auto"/> Planet-detection is in some cases limited by the [[asteroseismology|seismic pulsations]] of the star observed rather than by limitations of the instrument.<ref name="seis">{{cite journal | title=Asteroseismology of solar-type stars: particular physical effects | url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/1742-6596/118/1/012047/jpconf8_118_012047.pdf | author=Carrier | journal=Journal of Physics: Conference Series | volume=118 | date=2008 | doi=10.1088/1742-6596/118/1/012047 | last2=Eggenberger | first2=P | last3=Leyder | first3=J-C | pages=012047 | issue=1 |bibcode = 2008JPhCS.118a2047C }}</ref>
The principal investigator on HARPS is [[Michel Mayor]] who, along with [[Didier Queloz]] and [[Stéphane Udry]] have used the instrument to characterize the [[Gliese 581 planetary system]], home to one of the [[Gliese 581e|smallest known exoplanet]] orbiting a normal star, and two [[super-Earth]]s whose orbits lie in the star's [[habitable zone]].<ref name="mayor">{{cite journal <!--this is a preprint, paper is freely available via DOI link: | url=http://obswww.unige.ch/~udry/Gl581_preprint.pdf --> | author=Mayor | display-authors=etal | title=The HARPS search for southern extra-solar planets,XVIII. An Earth-mass planet in the [[GJ 581 planetary system]] | doi = 10.1051/0004-6361/200912172 | journal =[[Astronomy and Astrophysics]] | volume = 507 | number = 1 | pages = 487–494 | date=2009 | bibcode = 2009A&A...507..487M | arxiv = 0906.2780 }}</ref>
It was initially used for a survey of a thousand stars.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}
Since October 2012 the HARPS spectrograph has the precision to detect a new category of planets: Habitable super-Earths. This sensitivity was expected from simulations of stellar intrinsic signals, and actual observations of planetary systems. Currently, HARPS can detect habitable super-Earth only around low-mass stars as these are more affected by gravitational tug from planets and have habitable zones close to the host star.<ref name="ESO">{{cite web|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016Natur.536..437A|title=A terrestrial planet candidate in a temperate orbit around Proxima Centauri|author=|first=|authors=Pale Red Dot collaboration|date=August 2016|website=|publisher=Nature|arxiv=1609.03449|bibcode=2016Natur.536..437A|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
== Discoveries ==
