{{Psychology sidebar}}
'''Sense of direction''' is the ability to know one's location and perform [[wayfinding]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Definition of "sense of direction" {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|url = http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/sense-of-direction|website = www.collinsdictionary.com|accessdate = 2015-09-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Human Sense of Direction and Wayfinding|url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/1467-8306.9302009|journal = Annals of the Association of American Geographers|date = 2003-06-01|issn = 0004-5608|pages = 399–425|volume = 93|issue = 2|doi = 10.1111/1467-8306.9302009|first = Edward H.|last = Cornell|first2 = Autumn|last2 = Sorenson|first3 = Teresa|last3 = Mio}}</ref> It is related to [[cognitive map]]s, [[spatial awareness]], and [[spatial cognition]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sense of direction, spatial orientation, and cognitive maps.|url = http://psycnet.apa.org/journals/xhp/3/4/590/|website = Journal of Experimental Psychology: Human Perception and Performance|accessdate = 2015-09-15|last = Kozlowski|last2 = Bryant|date = 1977}}</ref>
Sense of direction can be impaired by brain damage, such as in the case of [[topographical disorientation]].

Humans create spatial maps whenever they go somewhere. Neurons called place cells inside the [[hippocampus]] fire individually while a person makes their way through an environment. This was first discovered in rats, when the neurons of the hippocampus were recorded. Certain neurons fired whenever the rat was in a certain area of its environment. These neurons form a grid when they are all put together on the same plane. 
We get our sense of direction when we match up spatial maps we have stored in the hippocampus, to the pattern of firing neurons when we are trying to find our way back or trying to find our car in the parking lot.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

== Santa Barbara Sense-of-Direction Scale ==
Sense of direction can be measured with the Santa Barbara Sense-of-Direction Scale,<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Development of a self-report measure of environmental spatial ability|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0160289602001162|journal = Intelligence|date = 2002-09-01|pages = 425–447|volume = 30|issue = 5|doi = 10.1016/S0160-2896(02)00116-2|first = Mary|last = Hegarty|first2 = Anthony E|last2 = Richardson|first3 = Daniel R|last3 = Montello|first4 = Kristin|last4 = Lovelace|first5 = Ilavanil|last5 = Subbiah}}</ref> a self-assessed psychometric test designed in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Santa Barbara Sense-of-Direction Scale {{!}} Hegarty Spatial Thinking Lab {{!}} Psychological & Brain Sciences {{!}} UC Santa Barbara|url = https://labs.psych.ucsb.edu/hegarty/mary/content/santa-barbara-sense-direction-scale|website = labs.psych.ucsb.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-15}}</ref> This scale has been used to study sense of direction in many contexts, such as driving.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Poor Sense of Direction Is Associated With Constricted Driving Space in Older Drivers|journal = The Journals of Gerontology Series B: Psychological Sciences and Social Sciences|date = 2009-05-01|issn = 1079-5014|pmc = 2670254|pmid = 19359596|pages = 348–355|volume = 64B|issue = 3|doi = 10.1093/geronb/gbp017|first = Kathleen A.|last = Turano|first2 = Beatriz|last2 = Munoz|first3 = Shirin E.|last3 = Hassan|first4 = Donald D.|last4 = Duncan|first5 = Emily W.|last5 = Gower|first6 = Karen B.|last6 = Roche|first7 = Lisa|last7 = Keay|first8 = Cynthia A.|last8 = Munro|first9 = Sheila K.|last9 = West}}</ref>

